homonymous hemianopia","Right monocular blindness"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct visual field defect is \u003Cstrong\u003Ebitemporal hemianopia\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs because a pituitary tumour compressing the optic chiasm affects the crossing nasal retinal fibres, which carry information from the temporal visual fields. The temporal retinal fibres (carrying nasal visual field information) remain unaffected as they do not cross at the chiasm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight homonymous hemianopia\u003C/strong\u003E - This results from unilateral damage to the left optic tract, lateral geniculate nucleus, or visual cortex\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft homonymous hemianopia\u003C/strong\u003E - This results from unilateral damage to the right optic tract, lateral geniculate nucleus, or visual cortex\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight monocular blindness\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs with complete right optic nerve lesions before the chiasm\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBinasal hemianopia\u003C/strong\u003E - This is rare and would require bilateral lesions affecting the uncrossed fibres in both optic tracts\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the anatomical arrangement of visual pathways is crucial for localising lesions based on visual field defects. Crossed fibres from nasal retina are particularly vulnerable to compression at the chiasm.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lesions affecting the optic chiasm typically cause bitemporal hemianopia due to compression of crossing nasal retinal fibres.","The optic chiasm is where nasal retinal fibres cross to the contralateral optic tract while temporal fibres remain ipsilateral.","Pituitary tumours commonly compress the optic chiasm from below, causing characteristic visual field defects."],"references":["Blumenfeld, H. Neuroanatomy through Clinical Cases, 2020, 3rd edition"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67786"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19086"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67786","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67786"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-30T12:34:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-30T12:34:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11820"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82633"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null